hands_on_practices.problem:
The benzene molecule, $\text{C}_6\text{H}_6$, is a planar aromatic hydrocarbon with a high degree of symmetry, belonging to the $D_{6h}$ point group. Consider a chemical modification where a single hydrogen atom is replaced by a chlorine atom to form chlorobenzene, $\text{C}_6\text{H}_5\text{Cl}$. This substitution reduces the molecule's symmetry.

For the purpose of this problem, let the benzene molecule lie in the $xy$-plane with its center at the origin. The principal six-fold rotation axis, $C_6$, is aligned with the $z$-axis. The carbon atoms are numbered C1 through C6 consecutively, with the C1 atom located on the positive $x$-axis. The substitution to form chlorobenzene occurs at the C1 position.

Which of the following lists contains exclusively symmetry operations that are present in benzene but are lost in chlorobenzene?

A. {$C_6$ (rotation by $60^\circ$ about $z$), $i$ (inversion through the origin), $\sigma_h$ (reflection through the molecular $xy$-plane)}
B. {$C_2$ (rotation by $180^\circ$ about $z$), $S_3$ (improper rotation by $120^\circ$ about $z$), $C_2'$ (rotation by $180^\circ$ about the $x$-axis passing through C1 and C4)}
C. {$S_6$ (improper rotation by $60^\circ$ about $z$), $i$ (inversion through the origin), $C_2''$ (rotation by $180^\circ$ about an axis bisecting the C2-C3 and C5-C6 bonds)}
D. {$C_3$ (rotation by $120^\circ$ about $z$), $\sigma_d$ (a diagonal reflection plane bisecting the C1-C2 and C4-C5 bonds), $\sigma_v$ (a vertical reflection plane containing the $x$-axis and $z$-axis)}
